This paper deals with combinatorial analysis of graph problems, specifically treewidth, and uses techniques from parameterized complexity. The paper also discusses structural graph measures such as feedback vertex set and vertex cover, which are commonly studied in discrete mathematics and graph theory (cs.DM). The study of treewidth is closely related to graph algorithms and data structures (cs.DS), and the paper discusses preprocessing rules for shrinking graphs, which is a common technique in computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper also uses concepts from computational complexity theory, such as NP-completeness and kernelization, which fall under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the paper discusses the theoretical properties of treewidth, which is a topic in graph theory and combinatorics (cs.GT).
